    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0d893cea_e600ab0d",
        "filename": "client/crashpad_client_linux.cc",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 461,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-06-08T16:10:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "1. You should really call sigaltstack to clear the alternate stack (or restore the previous one) before calling munmap, because the thread’s still running at this point and the configured sigaltstack becomes garbage after calling munmap.\n\n2. The destructor will still run even on threads that never called InitializeSignalStack. stack_mem will be nullptr in that case, and this will attempt to munmap kStackAllocSize bytes starting at address 0. You must null-check stack_mem in the destructor function.",
      "revId": "361dc6356c54c36f8395aafcb189d69783a8c431",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "64563303_088625e5",
        "filename": "client/crashpad_client_linux.cc",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 461,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-15T03:10:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "1. I now clear the alt stack if it matches the stack memory we\u0027re currently destructing. I don\u0027t restore the previous stack because we don\u0027t own that memory and don\u0027t know whether it still points to a valid stack. Maybe it\u0027s just been unmapped by another key\u0027s destructor or has been re-mapped for another purpose!\n\n2. This documentation says the destructor only gets called for threads with non-null values, which is consistent with my observations in the tests: https://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/009695399/functions/pthread_key_create.html",
      "parentUuid": "0d893cea_e600ab0d",
      "revId": "361dc6356c54c36f8395aafcb189d69783a8c431",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
